-- Sub-Saharan African Equities: Barclays Bank of Kenya, Diamond Trust Move
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k ,   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-10-14T16:19:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/sub-saharan-african-equitiess-barclays-bank-of-kenya-diamond-trust-move.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  increased for a fifth day, rising 0.2 percent to
24,485.17 by the 1 p.m. in Lagos, according to Bloomberg data.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  climbed for a ninth day, the
longest streak of gains since October last year, adding 1.3
percent to 1,860.2 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. Kenya’s
 All-Share Index  dropped less than 0.1 percent to 81.20 by 3 p.m.
in Nairobi. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  retreated 0.1
percent to 832.58 by the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek. The  Ghana
Stock Exchange  dropped for a second day, falling 1.6 percent to
6,756.37 by the 2 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Barclays Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (BCBL KN) rose 50 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 68.5 shillings, the highest since Sept. 29. The
lender signed an agreement with  Safaricom Ltd.  to offer a number
of services using the mobile-phone company’s money-transfer
service, M-PESA.  Barclays’ customers will be able to make deposits and
withdrawals using their mobile phones, the companies said in a
joint e-mailed statement yesterday.  Diamond Trust of Kenya Ltd.  (DTKL KN), a lender with
operations in four East African nations, rose 3 shillings, or
2.6 percent, to 120 shillings, the highest since May 1997, after
the Daily Nation newspaper reported it received $26 million from
International Finance Corp. to boost lending.  Diamond Trust’s units in Uganda and Tanzania will each
receive 240 million Kenyan shillings to provide trade finance to
small businesses that import goods to the region, the Nairobi-
based newspaper reported.  Safaricom Ltd.  (SAFCOM KN), Kenya’s biggest mobile-network
operator, rose for the first time in five days, adding 5 cents,
or 1 percent, to 4.9 shillings after saying it plans to expand
the marketing of mobile phone-based banking services, boosting
access to credit and insurance products for “unbanked
customers.”  Users of Safaricom’s M-Kesho, a mobile phone-based deposit-
taking program that pays interest, will be able to apply for 30-
day loans of between 100 shillings ($1.24) and 5,000 shillings
from about December,  Betty Mwangi-Thuo , chief of new products,
said in an interview from Nairobi, the capital, on Oct. 12.  To contact the reporters on this story:
